Introduction¶

Motivation and Overview¶

Around the world, education has been a fundamental cornerstone of human society for thousands of years. Education is the reason why future generations learn valuable skills and why we are studying Computer Science at the University of Maryland. As such, education has influences on many aspects of life in the present and future. For instance, children need to be educated in order to obtain certain jobs in the future. How countries handle this may influence the rate at which children are employed in the future, increasing or decreasing unemployment rates. Education also helps with starting future economic and societal growth and developing new knowledge and research. Furthermore, the basic idea of education promotes equality because everyone, regardless of their background, should inherit the knowledge and opportunities to grow personally and professionally.

See below a similar study that we wanted to build off of using up-to-date data:

  • https://www.jstor.org/stable/41613567 - 2012 Study by Earl Hunt from U.W. Seattle, linking genetics, economic development, culture, and education to a country's intelligence.

Several factors go into what makes a country’s education system unique. Mainly, it depends on the actual country. Typically, a country’s government allocates funds and resources to its education system in order to educate its youth. These funds are part of the country’s GDP, and depending on how those resources are distributed, they can greatly influence the type and amount a child is educated. Other factors impacting a country’s education system include literacy, completion, and enrollment rates. These metrics indicate how well a country’s education system is effective in a quantitative manner.

Acknowledging these factors it made us think: Does education affect IQ? For context, IQ (intelligence quotient) is a measure of human intelligence used to assess a person’s cognitive abilities. If that’s the case, which parts of education really play a factor in determining someone’s IQ? Could it be as simple as asking, “If a country puts more time and value into its education system, would that result in its citizens having higher IQs”? Wanting the answers to these questions, we decided to dedicate our Final Tutorial topic to the relationship between the factors of education systems and IQ.

This project aims to discover which factors related to education most significantly influence a person’s IQ through the Data Science lifecycle. Data collection and data processing will assist in obtaining as much relevant information as possible so that we can make reasonable claims about our data. Exploratory Data Analysis will help us discover the significance of relationships between factors such as unemployment, country location, etc, and how they could contribute to a person’s IQ. Then, we can analyze the data and conduct hypothesis testing to measure the significance of these relationships. Additionally, machine learning models, such as Linear Regression, Decision Trees, and Random Forests, will try to predict IQ based on some of these factors as independent variables. Lastly, we will provide recommendations on potential policy, future possibilities of continued research, and closing thoughts on our project.

Preliminary Research¶

Before taking a data-oriented look into this topic, it was important for us to look into the factors that play into building a strong education system.

Here are some of the resources we read up on:

  • https://theconversation.com/why-is-singapores-school-system-so-successful-and-is-it-a-model-for-the-west-22917 - Article by the Conversation on Singapore's educational success and philosophy
  • http://spice.fsi.stanford.edu/docs/japanese_education - Stanford University's take on Japanese Education, its achievements, and how it differs from the American education we're used to
  • https://www.smithsonianmag.com/innovation/why-are-finlands-schools-successful-49859555/ - An article by Smithsonian on the efficacy of Finland's individualized "whatever it takes" approach, honing in on students' weaknesses and ironing them out

Interpreting this can be a little confusing, as it doesn't clearly tell us whether there's a dependence on continent, i.e. neighboring countries, on IQ. We could interpret it as there being a dependence for all continents excluding Asia and North America, but even this is unclear.

Graph 3: Scatter Plots of IQ vs Percent GDP Spent on Education by Continent¶

Below, we'll create scatterplots in a similar manner, but separate them by continent and observe if there appears to be a dependence by continent.

We observe that primarily for Europe, there appears to be a positive trend between the Percent GDP Spent on Education and IQ. The presence or lack thereof of a correlation is hard to identify for the Oceania, North America, and South America graphs.

Graph 4: Scatter Plots of IQ vs Gross Primary and Tertiary Education Enrollment Rates¶

We'll create scatter plots of IQ vs Gross Education Enrollment Rates in similar fashion as above.

Gross Primary and Tertiary Education Enrollment Rates are defined as the percentage of the corresponding age groups that are enrolled in their respective education system. That is, for example, primary education usually spans ages 6-11, so the metric will calculate out of all people in the country aged 6-11, what percentage are enrolled in primary education? Hence, it's an important metric to show how accessible all levels of education are in a country and how that accessibility might affect the intelligence of its population.

Unfortunately, there is some missing data (see below) for gross primary and tertiary education enrollment (we will assume 0% means missing data). But, there are not too many of these so we can graph just the rows with data and still get a great idea of any correlation.

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Hypothesis Test 1: The relationship between Unemployment Rates and the Percent of GDP Spent on Education¶

We saw in the Exploratory Data Analysis section that Graph 8 was a scatter plot of Unemployment Rate vs. Percent of GDP Spent on Education. We want to explore the significance of this relationship because the graph appears that there could be a potential relationship between the two variables.

Here are our null and alternate hypotheses:

H0: There is no relationship between Unemployment Rate and the Percentage of GDP Spent on Education

H1: There is a relationship between Unemployment Rate and the Percentage of GDP Spent on Education

Let's run an ordinary least squares (OLS) regression between Unemployment Rate and Percent GDP Spent on Education to examine the significance of this relationship.

In [ ]:
# only include and plot countries where the unemployment rate data exists (not equal to 0)
nonzero_unemployment_countries = composite_df[composite_df['Unemployment_Rate'] != 0]

ols_results = statsmodels.formula.api.ols(formula="Unemployment_Rate ~ Percent_GDP_Education", data=nonzero_unemployment_countries).fit()
print(ols_results.summary())

                            OLS Regression Results

According to the results of the OLS regression, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that there is no relationship between Unemployment Rate and the Percentage of GDP Spent on Education. Looking at the p-value associated with Percent GDP Education variable, since that value is 0.087, it is larger than a 0.05 alpha value. This means that the relationship between Unemployment Rate and the Percentage of GDP Spent on Education is NOT statistically significant, and thus we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

As a result, it seems that there is no correlation between unemployment rate and percent of GDP spent on education. That's why it's important to not only look at graphs, but conduct statistical analysis to either affirm or disprove a correlationn.

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Hypothesis Test 2: The relationship between IQ and Gross Tertiary Education Enrollment¶

Another relationship that appeared to have some potential significance is IQ and Gross Tertiary Education Enrollment. Unlike Gross Primary Education Enrollment, Tertiary Education Enrollment appeared to have some positive correlation (according to Graph 4 in Exploratory Data Analysis). So, let's perform another OLS regression to examine the relationship between these two variables.

Here are our null and alternate hypotheses:

H0: There is no relationship between IQ and the Gross Tertiary Education Enrollment

H1: There is a relationship between IQ and the Gross Tertiary Education Enrollment

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Hypothesis Test 3: An interaction model between IQ and an interaction of Percent of GDP Spent on Education and Continent¶

It's also important to consider the interaction between variables that may influence IQ in our analysis. Take the interaction between Percent of GDP Spent on Education and Continent for example. Let's run another OLS regression and examine the results.

Again, here are our null and alternate hypotheses respectively:

H0: There is no relationship between IQ and the interaction of Percent of GDP Spent on Education and Continent.

H1: There is a relationship between IQ and the interaction of Percent of GDP Spent on Education and Continent.

That's interesting! According to the OLS regression results, the p-value associated with the interaction between Percent_GDP_Education and Continent changes depending on each continent and its data.

On one hand, the interaction between Percent_GDP_Education and Continent for Africa, Asia, Europe, and Oceania have associated p-values less than an alpha value of 0.05 (0.000, 0.007, 0.000, 0.028 respectively). This means that the relationship between IQ and the interaction is statistically significant. Thus, we can reject the null hypothesis for these continents specifically.

On the other hand, the interaction between Percent_GDP_Education and Continent for the Americas (North America and South America) have associated p-values greater than an alpha value of 0.05 (0.528 and 0.132 respectively). This means that the relationship between IQ and the interaction is NOT statistically significant. Thus, we fail to reject the null hypothesis for these continents specifically.

Analysis, Hypothesis Testing, and ML¶

Multivariate Regression 1: IQ vs Enrollment, Percent GDP, Unemployment Rate¶

Now, let's try to create a multivariate regression, where we predict IQ based on several other features, such as enrollment rates, percent GDP invested into education, and unemployment rates.

In [ ]:
#first, let's remove rows that have missing data
cleaned_df = composite_df[(composite_df['Gross_Primary_Education_Enrollment'] != 0) 
                          & (composite_df['Gross_Tertiary_Education_Enrollment'] != 0) 
                          & (composite_df['Unemployment_Rate'] != 0)]

#upon doing this, we have 160 rows without missing data, a decent amount considering we started with about 178.
len(cleaned_df)
Out[ ]:
160

Here, we'll store our features in X and our target in y, and use scikitlearn's train_test_split to randomly split the data into 90% training, 10% testing/validation. Since we have a relatively small amount of data to train on, we want to ensure there's enough to train on, so we'll use 90% of our data for training. Note that typically, an 80-20 (training-test) split would be ideal.

We then use this split data to train the Linear Regression and print out the coefficients/intercept.

In [ ]:
X = cleaned_df[['Gross_Primary_Education_Enrollment', 
                'Gross_Tertiary_Education_Enrollment',
                'Unemployment_Rate',
                'Percent_GDP_Education']]
y = cleaned_df['IQ']

#Observe that we split with random_state=1, which we'll keep consistent throughout our ML section so
#we can accurately comment on and compare our models
#Note that this is not necessarily best practice in the real world, but we will do so for consistency.
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.1, random_state=1)
firstmod1 = LinearRegression()
firstmod1.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(f'Coefficients (Gross_Primary_Education_Enrollment, Gross_Tertiary_Education_Enrollment, Unemployment_Rate, Percent_GDP_Education): {firstmod1.coef_}')
print(f'Intercept: {firstmod1.intercept_}')

Coefficients (Gross_Primary_Education_Enrollment, Gross_Tertiary_Education_Enrollment, Unemployment_Rate, Percent_GDP_Education): [ -0.07499135   0.31082261  -0.36704666 -59.20267916]
Intercept: 82.81716092126408

We'll now use this trained model to predict y values (y_pred), then test them against the true y values (y_test).

This R^2 value is perfect, telling us that the decision tree perfectly predicts all of our test data. This could very well mean our tree is overfitting to the test data and that is why it's doing so bad on the test data. Let's fix this.

With a decision tree, we can prevent overfitting using a few hyperparameters provided in sklearn. More specifically, we can use hyperparameters like "max_depth" and "min_samples_leaf" to make sure the tree doesn't have too many levels and each leaf has a specific number of samples, respectively.

In [ ]:
# limit max depth to 10 and make sure each leaf has 5 samples minimum
model_decisiontree2 = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=50, max_depth=10, min_samples_leaf=5) 
model_decisiontree2.fit(X_train, y_train)

Policy and Insight¶

Conclusions/Observations¶

Having written this notebook, we’ve gained a greater appreciation for the effect of educational investment on literacy, IQ, and unemployment. We recognize the significance of our findings and hope that they can be used to positively influence educational policy worldwide. More information on the importance of investment can be found in the following article (https://www.csis.org/analysis/investing-quality-education-economic-development-peace-and-stability), one of our inspirations for writing this notebook.

Our data analysis, surprisingly, at first did not yield a correlation between the percent of GDP invested into education and IQ. The data appeared almost random, with outliers on both ends. Countries like Sierra Leone spent a larger chunk of their GDP on education than most others, yet still had one of the lowest average IQs, whereas countries like Singapore spent less than most others on education, but still had the second highest average IQ. But as we investigated more factors, such as enrollment and completion rates, especially for different levels of schooling, our logical conclusion was reaffirmed: investment in education does indeed affect IQ.

We realized that it’s not as simple as “investing x% more in education increases average IQ by y points”, but rather as a product of several factors, such as continent, unemployment rates, enrollment rates, completion rates, location, and etc. A few of these, namely enrollment rates, completion rates, and unemployment rates, can quite clearly be linked to the country’s investment into education, not as a matter of proportion, but rather the internal allocation of the proportion set aside for education: how much is dedicated towards teachers, how much towards educational technology, how much towards extracurricular programs, how much towards outreach and education for underserved populations? Also, things like completion rates and gross enrollment rates are inherently not only linked to monetary investment into education but also how society in said country views education as a whole. That is, a country’s culture must strongly encourage children to pursue a full secondary education, and hopefully even beyond. Also, their policies must make education unequivocally available to its entire population, regardless of factors like class and gender so that most of their population has the ability and support to make it fully through their schooling system.

Next Steps¶

Through an extension of our research, we could likely discover and explain the several economic/spending factors that influence IQ and employment. We could also analyze the intelligence correlation based on other metrics, say IB or PISA scores, considering that IQ has long been a disputed system of measuring intelligence. See the following two articles for conflicting arguments on this matter:

  • https://som.yale.edu/news/2009/11/why-high-iq-doesnt-mean-youre-smart - Yale Study that argues that IQ is a bad measure of intelligence
  • https://www.science.org/content/article/what-does-iq-really-measure#:~:text=A%20new%20study%20argues%20that%20the%20score%20reflects%20both%20motivation%20and%20intelligence&text=Kids%20who%20score%20higher%20on,even%20greater%20health%2C%20and%20longevity - Science.org Article in favor of IQ as an intelligence metric and as a metric of how motivated a person is

Such a detailed report would provide us with further insight into how countries with low IQ to educational investment efficiencies could learn from other, more “successful” countries’ educational models. We believe this is quite a major issue and that further statistical/data analysis could be a key step towards greater and equitable educational opportunity worldwide.

On that note, it's worth mentioning the plethora of benefits education brings to masses. Although many think it's a matter of just helping a person get a job, there's actually much more to it, as these articles detail:

  • https://www.federalreserve.gov/publications/2019-economic-well-being-of-us-households-in-2018-higher-education.htm - A government study that takes the general notion of "the more the education, the higher the salary" a step further by analyzing how fiscally secure people feel
  • https://www.uopeople.edu/blog/benefits-of-education-are-societal-and-personal/ - A University of the People article that goes beyond financial matters, talking about the many societal and personal gains a person attains by staying in school

So, the next time you're considering not going to school or a class, remember that education is a privilege we're lucky to have, and we should value it.

In the words of Edward St John, "Education has the power to transform lives and provides the foundation for success".
